Bayesian modeling and prediction for movies

Setup

Load data

load("movies.Rdata")

Part 1: Data

This dataset is a sample of 651 films released between 1970 and 2014.

count(movies)
## # A tibble: 1 x 1
##       n
##   <int>
## 1   651
summary(movies$thtr_rel_year)
##    Min. 1st Qu.  Median    Mean 3rd Qu.    Max. 
##    1970    1990    2000    1998    2007    2014

For all these movies several pieces of information have been collected regarding their year/month/day of released (in theatres and on DVD); the assessment they have received in two websites (Rotten Tomatoes and IMDb); so as many other features such as director, Oscar’s award, and the like. As for the information concerning the rating of the movies, it comes from two sources. Either it was willingly “watchers” of these movies who rated them based on their particular experience (this works for the audience scores/rating of Rotten Tomatoes and for the IMDb rating); or professional critics who rated them (see the variables critics_score, critics_rating). Because nothing makes imposible that the same persons may rate these movies in both websites, association between the two might be simply redundant or not interesting at all. However, we will assume that these websites adress different public and, therefore, the scores in one are not a simple repetition of the score in the other.

As for the generabizability of the result, given the size of the sample, hardly could we extrapolate results if we subdivided the sample by certain variable (for instance, genre). However, 651 random cases is enough to generalize when it comes to talk about the movies as a whole. Conversely, as the information is based on observational data, no causalities can be inferred from this dataset. Exclusively assocation between the variables is feasible based on this dataset.

Part 3: Exploratory data analysis

Audience score (univariate exploration)

summary_aud_score <- movies %>% summarise(mean_x = mean(audience_score), sd_x = sd(audience_score), median_x = median(audience_score), min_x = min(audience_score), max_x = max(audience_score), skew_x = skewness(audience_score))
round(summary_aud_score, 2)
## # A tibble: 1 x 6
##   mean_x  sd_x median_x min_x max_x skew_x
##    <dbl> <dbl>    <dbl> <dbl> <dbl>  <dbl>
## 1  62.36 20.22       65    11    97  -0.36
ggplot(data = movies, aes(x = audience_score)) + geom_histogram(binwidth = 1, colour = "black", aes(y = ..density.., fill = ..count..)) + geom_density(alpha = .6) + scale_fill_gradient("Frequency", low= adjustcolor("#FFFFFF", alpha = .1), high= adjustcolor("#3399CC", alpha = .9)) + stat_function(fun = dnorm, colour = "red", args = list(mean = mean(movies$audience_score), sd = sd(movies$audience_score))) + ggtitle("Audience Score")

As we see above, audience score is a numeric variable. Its mean equals 62.36, however the values of the variable are highly spread; in addition, the distribution is left-skewed.

Given that what we have are five dichotomous variables, on the one hand, and a numeric variable, on the other, there are two ways of exploring their relationships: either exploring the measures of location and spread of the later by the two levels of the former (graphically: a box-and-whiskers plot); or by means of a logistic regression. We conducted both in all five cases:

As we can see, between feature_film and audience_score there is a substantive negative association of more than 20 points of difference. The box-and-whiskers plot shows that setting aside a couple of non-feature films whose score is very low (less than 25), more than three-fourths of the distributions is above 75. Half of feature films, on the contrary, find themselves below an audience score of 62.

One potential problems here is the fact that the number of cases are very unevenly distributed between the two levels of feature_film. More than nine-tenths of the cases are feature films (591 out of 651). This might make the found association less reliable.

Part 4: Modeling

Full model

In order to conduct the process of model selection, we implemented the BMA (Bayesian model averaging). We assigned equal probabilities to all models (modelprior = uniform), and we use as criteria for being included in the final model the Bayesian Information Criterion (prior = “BIC”), that is to say, the model will be that with the lowest BIC.

bma_aud_score <- bas.lm(audience_score ~ feature_film + drama + runtime + mpaa_rating_R + thtr_rel_year + oscar_season + summer_season + imdb_rating + imdb_num_votes + critics_score + best_pic_nom + best_pic_win + best_actor_win + best_actress_win + best_dir_win + top200_box, data = na.omit(movies), prior = "BIC", modelprior = uniform())
bma_aud_score
## 
## Call:
## bas.lm(formula = audience_score ~ feature_film + drama + runtime +     mpaa_rating_R + thtr_rel_year + oscar_season + summer_season +     imdb_rating + imdb_num_votes + critics_score + best_pic_nom +     best_pic_win + best_actor_win + best_actress_win + best_dir_win +     top200_box, data = na.omit(movies), prior = "BIC", modelprior = uniform())

As we can see above, apart form the intercept, there are three variables whose marginal posterior probability is above 0.50: imdb_rating (1.00), critics_score (0.92) and runtime (0.51). This is also obvious in the fourth chart plotting marginal inclusion probability by inclusion probabilities.

plot(bma_aud_score, which = 1, add.smooth = TRUE)

As we see in the plot of the residuals, it appears that there might be three outliers in the data: observations 122, 206, and 239.

The posterior probability of the most likely model, that including imdb_rating, critics_score and runtime is 17.6%; the second model (the same but excluding runtime) has a posterior probability of 15.3%. Both together accumulate approximately one-third of the total posterior probability. The following model, on the contrary, one represents a posterior probability of 3.6%.

image(bma_aud_score, rotate = FALSE)

When we have a look at the chart (model rank), it seems obvious that imdb_rating and critics_score are to be included in the refined models (they appear in most of the first models, those with higher log posterior odds). Runtime, on the contrary, looks like a less reliable variable.

This confirms what we suggested above, runtime’s distribution is much closer to zero than the other two variables. Its inclusion in the final model, then, might be disputable.

Part 5: Prediction

For the prediction, we chose the movie “Captain Fantastic” (2016). This movie has been assessed with an 82 by the critics and a 85 by the audience. It lasts 119 minutes and it was scored with 8.0 at IMDb (sources: https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/captain_fantastic#contentReviews; and http://www.imdb.com/title/tt3553976/).

capFan <- data.frame(audience_score = 85, critics_score = 82, runtime = 119, imdb_rating = 8.0)
capFan_pre <- predict.bas(best_model, newdata = capFan, estimator = "BMA", se.fit = TRUE)
capFan_pre$fit
##          [,1]
## [1,] 86.12095

As we can see, the model predicts the score of the film to be 86.12, a bit over the 85 (the actual score).

Part 6: Conclusion

The analysis shown above constitute one of the many models can be achieved employing a Bayesian persepctives. We limited ourselves to the use of BMA and BIC (which tries to balance accuracy in prediction with parsimony in the model), but several others criteria could be employed (e.g. BPM, HPM, and the like instead of BMA; or ZS-null instead of the BIC). The model shows that, from the many avaialble variables, three of them (runtime, critics_score and imdb_rating) constitute the best combination in BIC terms to predict the audience_score of a given movie. Particularly, the positive association between audience_score and imdb_rating is evident (being its posterior probability of being included in any model almost indisputable). Runtime and critics_score shown a weaker association, nevertheless, their contributions improve the predictions made by imdb_rating on its own.

One potential weakness of the model presented is the existance of three outliers in the data (122, 206, 239). We decided to keep them in the model despite the fact that they might well influence the association presented here.
